    <p class="eyebrow">Water Safety Education</p>
    <h1>Education that meets people where they are.</h1>
    <p class="lead">Effective water safety education saves lives when it is age-appropriate, evidence-informed, and delivered by people who understand the real mechanisms.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container grid grid-3">
    <article class="card">
      <h2>Age-Appropriate Learning</h2>
      <p>RiP is creating education that aligns with developmental stages and existing safety frameworks, including Grade 3 curriculum concepts and programs such as Swim to Survive.</p>
      <ul class="feature-list">
        <li>Younger learners focus on recognizing unsafe water conditions.</li>
        <li>Students learn when not to enter the water.</li>
        <li>Lessons introduce basic self-rescue principles in clear language.</li>
      </ul>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <h2>Older Students & Adults</h2>
      <p>For older students and adults, education expands into identifying rip current risk factors and understanding how weather, wind, waves, and structures influence water conditions.</p>
      <p>Our goal is not to create fear, but to build confidence through knowledge and understanding.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <h2>Classroom & Beach-Based Learning</h2>
      <p>Classroom learning builds the foundation. Beach-based learning helps participants observe real conditions, identify hazards, and practice decision-making in a safe, supervised environment.</p>
    </article>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-muted">
  <div class="container grid grid-2">
    <div>
      <p class="eyebrow">Evidence-Informed Messaging</p>
      <h2>Public education should be accurate, practical, and local.</h2>
    </div>
    <div>
      <p>All RiP educational content is grounded in current research and real-world coastal science. We work closely with leading experts to ensure information shared with the public is accurate, practical, and relevant to the Great Lakes.</p>
      <p>This includes collaboration with Dr. Chris Houser, Dean of Science at the University of Waterloo and a leading authority on rip current dynamics. By sharing evidence-informed messaging presented by Great Lakes lifeguards who have responded to dangerous current emergencies, RiP helps bridge science and public safety.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

